The resulting nonwoven fabrics (S1–S3) varied primarily in areal density and thickness: S1 was the lightest, S2 exhibited intermediate areal density and thickness, and S3 was the thickest. Despite these variations, all three maintained a consistently high porosity (> 99%), a feature typical of natural fiber-based insulations [14]. Their detailed characteristics are summarized in Table 1

